Conclusion
This is a critical bug affecting heavy subagent users. The fix requires parsing TWO types of subagent data:

Sidechain entries (isSidechain: true) - The actual subagent activity with full token details
Tool result summaries (toolUseResult) - Aggregated totals reported back by the subagent

The Complete Picture
In our test case:

Main agent: Uses claude-opus-4-1-20250805 (expensive model)
Subagent: Uses claude-sonnet-4-20250514 (cheaper model)
Main agent tokens: Regular entries without isSidechain flag
Subagent tokens: 63 entries with isSidechain: true containing 1,086,368 tokens
Tool result summary: Reports 38,203 tokens (likely excluding cache tokens)

CRITICAL: Subagents can run on different models than the main agent! The code-reviewer subagent used Sonnet while the main session used Opus. This has massive cost implications - Opus is significantly more expensive than Sonnet.
The mystery of "missing tokens" is solved: they were there all along, in TWO places:

As individual isSidechain entries (full detail)
As toolUseResult summaries (aggregated)

Currently, ccusage counts the sidechain entries but doesn't identify them as subagent activity, making it impossible to distinguish between main agent and subagent usage. The tool result summaries are completely ignored.
Priority Fix

Immediate: Filter entries by isSidechain flag to separate subagent tokens
Important: Parse toolUseResult for validation and summary data
Nice-to-have: Show breakdown by individual subagent tasks

